<li role="presentation"><a href='?term="Curr%20Opin%20Ophthalmol"[jour]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem" data-add-to-search="true">Add to search</a></li>
</ul></nav></section><section class="front-matter"><div class="ameta p font-secondary font-xs">
<hgroup><h1>Gaps in standards for integrating artificial intelligence technologies into ophthalmic practice</h1></hgroup><div class="cg p">
<a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Baxter%20SL"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id1"><span class="name western">Sally L Baxter</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id1">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Sally L Baxter</span>, <span class="degrees">MD, MSc</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Viterbi Family Department of Ophthalmology and Shiley Eye Institute, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, CA, USA</div>
<div class="p">
<sup>2</sup>Health Department of Biomedical Informatics, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, CA, USA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Baxter%20SL"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Sally L Baxter</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1,</sup><sup>2</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Lee%20AY"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id2"><span class="name western">Aaron Y Lee</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id2">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Aaron Y Lee</span>, <span class="degrees">MD, MSCI</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>3</sup>Department of Ophthalmology, University of Washington, Seattle, WA, USA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Lee%20AY"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Aaron Y Lee</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>3</sup>
</div>
<ul class="d-buttons inline-list">
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="aip_a" aria-expanded="false">Author information</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="clp_a" aria-expanded="false">Copyright and License information</button></li>
</ul>
<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="A1">
<sup>1</sup>Viterbi Family Department of Ophthalmology and Shiley Eye Institute, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, CA, USA</div>
<div id="A2">
<sup>2</sup>Health Department of Biomedical Informatics, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, CA, USA</div>
<div id="A3">
<sup>3</sup>Department of Ophthalmology, University of Washington, Seattle, WA, USA</div>
<div class="author-notes p"><div class="fn" id="CR1">
<sup>✉</sup><p class="display-inline"><strong>Corresponding Author</strong>: Aaron Y. Lee, Box 359608, 325 Ninth Ave., Seattle, WA 98104, <span>leeay@uw.edu</span></p>
</div></div>
</div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div></div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC8373825  NIHMSID: NIHMS1718437  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34231531/" class="usa-link">34231531</a>
</div>
<div class="ra xbox p" role="complementary" aria-label="Related or updated information about this article"><div>The publisher's version of this article is available at <a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/ICU.0000000000000781" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Curr Opin Ophthalmol</a>
</div></div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="ABS1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<section id="S1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Purpose of review:</h3>
<p id="P1">The purpose of this review is to provide an overview of healthcare standards and their relevance to multiple ophthalmic workflows, with a specific emphasis on describing gaps in standards development needed for improved integration of artificial intelligence (AI) technologies into ophthalmic practice.</p></section><section id="S2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Recent findings:</h3>
<p id="P2">Healthcare standards are an essential component of data exchange and critical for clinical practice, research, and public health surveillance activities. Standards enable interoperability between clinical information systems, healthcare information exchange between institutions, and clinical decision support in a complex health information technology ecosystem. There are several gaps in standards in ophthalmology, including relatively low adoption of imaging standards, lack of use cases for integrating apps providing AI-based decision support, lack of common data models to harmonize big data repositories, and no standards regarding interfaces and algorithmic outputs.</p></section><section id="S3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Summary:</h3>
<p id="P3">These gaps in standards represent opportunities for future work to develop improved data flow between various elements of the digital health ecosystem. This will enable more widespread adoption and integration of AI-based tools into clinical practice. Engagement and support from the ophthalmology community for standards development will be important for advancing this work.</p></section><section id="kwd-group1" class="kwd-group"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong> artificial intelligence, imaging, informatics, standards, interoperability, ophthalmology</p></section></section><section id="S4"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Introduction</h2>
<p id="P4">Innovations in artificial intelligence (AI) algorithms have exponentially increased with the widespread digitization of healthcare data. The literature describing AI algorithms and models for ophthalmic applications, particularly in automated imaging diagnosis, is ever-increasing(<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>,<a href="#R2" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R2">2</a>). However, the implementation of AI-based technologies into clinical ophthalmic practice is still in relatively early stages. For widespread deployment to be possible, standards need to be developed to enable seamless and automated communication between devices and information systems such as electronic health records (EHRs), imaging systems, and decision support systems.</p>
<p id="P5">Here, we will provide an overview of healthcare standards and the need for information exchange between different systems (<a href="#F1" class="usa-link">Figure</a>). We will describe some applications for AI-based technologies in ophthalmic workflows and describe key gaps in standards development. We hope to highlight opportunities for future work to enhance the implementation and impact of AI in day-to-day clinical practice.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F1"><h3 class="obj_head">Figure. Integration of AI models into the healthcare ecosystem.</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><img class="graphic" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/fafe/8373825/c5410be56f96/nihms-1718437-f0001.jpg" loading="lazy" height="1920" width="1845" alt="Figure."></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p id="P38">A representative sample of information flow between healthcare modalities and the standards that can drive their interoperability.</p></figcaption></figure></section><section id="S5"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Standards: What are they and why do we need them?</h2>
<p id="P6">Healthcare standards enable communication and information exchange essential to clinical care(<a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3**</a>). Key definitions relevant to healthcare standards are in <a href="#T1" class="usa-link">Table 1</a>, and some concepts related to standards are detailed below.</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T1"><h3 class="obj_head">Table 1. Key Definitions related to Healthcare Standards.</h3>
<div class="caption p"><p id="P39">These are examples and descriptions of healthcare standards and clinical terminologies, as well as other abbreviations commonly encountered when discussing healthcare data exchange.</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="box" rules="all">
<colgroup span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
</colgroup>
<thead><tr>
<th align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Abbreviation/Common Name</th>
<th align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Full Name</th>
<th align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Brief Description</th>
</tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<strong>API</strong>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Application Programming Interface</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Interface/software intermediary allowing two applications to interact and exchange information</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<strong>CDA</strong>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Clinical Document Architecture</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Framework for sharing clinical documents that contain both human-readable text and machine-readable XML; important for health information exchange for data transfer between different institutions</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<strong>CPT</strong>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Current Procedural Terminology</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Codes related to procedures, tasks, or services provided in the course of clinical care that can be used for tracking/reporting or billing</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<strong>DICOM</strong>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Standard for storage, exchange, and transmission of medical images</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<strong>EHR</strong>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Electronic Health Record</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">System for making “transactions” (i.e. orders) related to clinical care, enabling documentation of clinical care, and storing data related to care</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<strong>FHIR</strong>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resource</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Specification for exchanging healthcare data, and includes both clinical components and administrative/infrastructure components</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<strong>HIE</strong>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Health Information Exchange</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Networks to exchange health information for shared patients with health data in different information systems at different institutions</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<strong>HL-7</strong>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Health Level Seven International</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Organization focused on developing standards for exchange, integration, sharing, and retrieval of electronic health information</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<strong>ICD</strong>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">International Statistical Classification of Diseases and Related Health Problems</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">International standards for reporting diseases and health conditions in a comprehensive, hierarchical fashion; designed for output/reporting</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<strong>IHE</strong>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Integrating the Healthcare Enterprise</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Organization centered on developing “profiles” to define how different systems should cooperate and share information</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<strong>LOINC</strong>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Logical Observation Identifiers Names and Codes</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Standards for medical laboratory observations, microbiology tests, clinical concepts, clinical documents, and survey instruments; 6-part name given to each observation identity</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<strong>PACS</strong>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Picture archiving and communication system</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">System that provides storage and access to images, including the imaging modalities, a secured network for transmitting patient information, workstations/interfaces for reviewing images, and archives for storing images</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<strong>RxNorm</strong>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">N/A</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Standards using normalized names for clinical drugs and allowing linkage between different drug vocabularies</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<strong>SMART on FHIR</strong>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Substitutable Medical Applications, Reusable Technologies (SMART) on Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resource (FHIR)</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Standards for formalizing the process for how apps interact with FHIR interfaces, how they launch within an EHR, and standardizing security protocols for data exchange</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
<strong>SNOMED</strong>
</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Systematized Nomenclature of Medicine</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Reference terminology for medical concepts designed to codify input into EHRs</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section><section id="S6"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Interoperability</h3>
<p id="P7">Standards allow interoperability between different information systems. For example, laboratory measurements need to be transferred from laboratory information systems and the devices that are directly acquiring measurements to EHR systems for clinician viewing, without requiring the clinician to log into the original laboratory system or physically access the device. The Logical Observation Identifiers Names and Codes (LOINC) standard is a coding system that allows electronic transactions between independent computer systems involving laboratory and other clinical measures(<a href="#R4" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R4">4</a>–<a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">6</a>).</p>
<p id="P8">Another key example highly relevant for ophthalmology is communicating information from imaging devices. The international standard for biomedical imaging data is the Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine (DICOM) standard(<a href="#R7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R7">7</a>). The standards include not only descriptors of the image itself, but also defines network services for exchange, storage, and access to images; standards for products of image analysis applications; and standards for imaging department workflow management.</p>
<p id="P9">Clinical terminologies are standards relatively more well-known to clinicians. These include diagnosis codes, such as the International Classification of Disease (ICD)(<a href="#R8" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R8">8</a>) and the Systemized Nomenclature of Medicine (SNOMED)(<a href="#R9" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R9">9</a>), as well as procedure codes, such as Current Procedural Terminology (CPT)(<a href="#R10" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R10">10</a>). These enable consistency in clinical documentation, billing, research, and public health reporting. Although there are known challenges with diagnosis and procedure coding, such as incomplete or inconsistent coding(<a href="#R11" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R11">11</a>), the lack of standards would make essential tasks such as billing exponentially more challenging.</p>
<p id="P10">One of the key standards underlying interoperability is the Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources (FHIR) Specification(<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a>), which entails a set of modules that encompasses items like security and privacy, terminology, administration, clinical content, medications, diagnostics, workflow, and financial, among others. The FHIR specification also describes exchangeable content as “resources” that include a commonly formatted definition, metadata, and human readable portions. FHIR is a data exchange standard that can be used standalone or in combination with other existing standards.</p></section><section id="S7"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Health Information Exchange (HIE)</h3>
<p id="P11">Information also needs to be communicated between different EHR systems, such as when a patient receives clinical care at multiple locations that do not share the same information technology (IT) infrastructure. This is the central concept underlying HIE(<a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">13</a>). This led to the development of the Clinical Document Architecture (CDA)(<a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">14</a>), an XML-based standard for encoding clinical documents to facilitate healthcare data exchange to different institutions and to regulatory authorities.</p></section><section id="S8"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Clinical Decision Support within and outside of EHRs</h3>
<p id="P12">An important application of health IT tools is to provide clinical decision support (CDS) to clinicians, often at the point of care(<a href="#R15" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R15">15</a>). Input data (such as patient demographics or relevant clinical variables) are fed through an inference engine (such as a linear model or AI system), which then produces an output for the clinician, such as a risk estimation and/or a recommendation for subsequent management. For CDS tools internal to EHR systems, the input data, inference engine, and output all live within the same system. However, in the modern digital health era and Internet of Things (IoT), increasingly there are more iterations of all of these components(<a href="#R16" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R16">16</a>). For example, patients may have monitoring devices at home that provide input data rather than measurements conducted in clinical laboratories(<a href="#R17" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R17">17</a>,<a href="#R18" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R18">18</a>). Input data may also come from surveys in patient portals(<a href="#R19" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R19">19</a>). The number of mobile and wearable applications related to health and clinical decision support are exponentially increasing(<a href="#R20" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R20">20</a>), and these may draw from various input data sources as well, including EHRs. Often these mobile apps have inference engines that live outside the EHR system, so standards are needed to facilitate the input of data from various sources. Similarly, once the inference engine has run and produced an output, again standards are needed for those outputs to be transferred back to EHRs or other systems. Because each app may have its own proprietary specifications, integrating apps with EHR systems on a custom, case-by-case basis would lead to enormous cost and effort, and thereby limit adoption. The recognition of this problem has led to the development of SMART on FHIR(<a href="#R21" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R21">21</a>), which centers on application programming interfaces (APIs) where standards allow apps to “plug-and-play” to various information systems and achieve effective data flow without requiring custom interface development.</p>
<p id="P13">Taken together, there is a complex healthcare information ecosystem (<a href="#F1" class="usa-link">Figure</a>) wherein data need to flow between different components. Standards allow different systems to “talk” to one another and ensure that data are generated, transferred, and stored in a consistent manner without needing to customize each data exchange. This is important not only for clinical care, but also for secondary applications of health data such as research and public health surveillance.</p></section></section><section id="S9"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Gaps in Standards for Integrating AI into Clinical Workflows</h2>
<p id="P14">Even if an AI algorithm or model has excellent performance in isolation, its impact will be limited without successful integration within the larger health IT ecosystem. Here, we will describe some areas where AI may be applied into ophthalmic workflows and associated gaps in standards development and/or implementation.</p>
<section id="S10"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Imaging</h3>
<p id="P15">Imaging has become a core component of ophthalmic practice. A wide range of AI models have been developed to automate diagnoses of various types of images, to segment anatomic components or identify lesions within images, and to predict disease progression in a variety of contexts(<a href="#R22" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R22">22</a>–<a href="#R24" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R24">24</a>). However, besides assisting with imaging analysis and interpretation, AI could also be used for streamlining imaging workflows, such as facilitating ordering and scheduling (for instance, automatically generating orders for patients with diabetes to undergo retinal imaging annually).</p>
<p id="P16">Currently, there are major gaps in ophthalmic imaging standards. DICOM standards are recognized international standards for medical imaging, yet ophthalmology manufacturers’ adoption of DICOM remains disappointingly low, particularly compared to other imaging-centric specialties such as radiology or cardiology(<a href="#R25" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R25">25*</a>). The DICOM standard specifies a description of the image, patient demographic information, the image capture protocol, and relevant outputs such as algorithmically derived measurements(<a href="#R7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R7">7</a>). While it has become commonplace for ophthalmic devices to accept patient demographic information through DICOM modality worklist, ophthalmic devices seldom include adoption of the standards that would facilitate data transfer in and out of imaging devices to other information systems(<a href="#R25" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R25">25</a>). Frequently, the imaging or measurement data are not readable without proprietary software or custom interfaces. There are currently no standards by which specific ophthalmic clinical data from EHR systems can be exchanged to augment analytics. Even in cases a manufacturer has developed a DICOM interface, it is frequently not included as a standard feature and requires further investment in the form of manufacturer-specific PACS or DICOM module, leading to low adoption by ophthalmology practices. Plus, the prevailing model in ophthalmic devices for the analytic software to be built into the devices. Without a wide adoption of standards that allow third-party algorithms to access the data, this model will likely continue, further hindering implementation of imaging-based AI algorithm into clinical practice.</p></section><section id="S11"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Clinical Decision Support (CDS)</h3>
<p id="P17">With the vast quantities of data now available with widespread adoption of EHRs and other digital health tools(<a href="#R26" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R26">26</a>–<a href="#R28" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R28">28</a>), numerous predictive models have been developed across a range of clinical applications(<a href="#R29" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R29">29</a>). These models aim to improve identification and risk stratification of patients. CDS involves embedding these models into health IT systems for facilitating real-time risk prediction, at the point of care. This “prediction technology” and real-time CDS is one of the key anticipated benefits of AI in improving healthcare(<a href="#R30" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R30">30</a>). Particularly with the increasing use of machine learning and deep learning, these AI-based algorithms have the potential to improve predictive performance and further advance a precision approach to treatment. However, a recent systematic review of predictive models embedded into EHR systems found that only 10% of implemented models used machine learning or deep learning(<a href="#R31" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R31">31*</a>), demonstrating the nascent nature of this application.</p>
<p id="P18">As mentioned previously, there are increasing complexities to data flow (and subsequently to CDS interventions) with a growing digital health environment that expands beyond EHRs. As such, use of standards will become increasingly important to allow data exchange necessary for AI algorithms to provide appropriate and timely CDS. This is a growth area for ophthalmology, as our recent review of the literature yielded zero publications describing SMART on FHIR standards applied to CDS interventions relevant to ophthalmology. As AI-based tools continue to advance for ophthalmic applications, more investigation is needed to develop use cases and describe best practices.</p></section><section id="S12"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Harmonizing Big Data Repositories</h3>
<p id="P19">Many AI algorithms, particularly those leveraging deep learning techniques, are “data-hungry” and require large volumes of training data to achieve high performance(<a href="#R32" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R32">32</a>). Training data may consist of imaging data, EHR data, or unstructured/narrative data, depending on the context and the anticipated application of the AI algorithm. We have already mentioned how the relative lack of DICOM adoption has hindered the advancement of AI for imaging, and one manifestation of this lies in the difficulty of developing datasets comprised of images from different imaging devices or PACS systems. Developing those datasets is currently an effort-intensive, manual process in the absence of appropriate DICOM standards adoption.</p>
<p id="P20">In the realm of EHR data, the recognition of the need for big data repositories to drive innovation in AI and allow development of improved algorithms that require massive amounts of data from numerous patients has led to the development of “common data models,” such as the Informatics for Integrating Biology &amp; the Bedside (i2b2) model(<a href="#R33" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R33">33</a>,<a href="#R34" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R34">34</a>) or the Observation Medical Outcomes Partnership (OMOP) data model(<a href="#R35" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R35">35</a>,<a href="#R36" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R36">36</a>), to provide a standard unifying data from disparate sources using different EHR systems. This allows merging of data from multiple institutions and organizations to create large central data repositories, such as the NIH All of Us Research Program(<a href="#R37" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R37">37</a>). Even when institutions may not be directly sharing data with each other to create a shared central data repository, the mapping of data to a shared data model allows distributed or federated analyses to be performed and ensures consistency in definitions of clinical variables, such as what has been done by the pSCANNER consortium(<a href="#R38" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R38">38</a>). However, big datasets in ophthalmology – such as the Intelligent Research in Sight (IRIS) registry hosted by the American Academy of Ophthalmology(<a href="#R39" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R39">39</a>) and the Sight Outcomes Research Collaborative (SOURCE) Ophthalmology Electronic Health Record Data Repository hosted by the University of Michigan(<a href="#R40" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R40">40</a>,<a href="#R41" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R41">41</a>) – have not adopted a common data model. The lack of standards means that these ophthalmic datasets cannot “cross-talk” with each other, nor can they be easily combined with existing datasets that use a common data model. One reason why a common data model has not been adopted could be that the existing models do not adequately address the needs of ophthalmology. Additionally, development of the OMOP model was still in its infancy when the IRIS registry first started. Our field would likely benefit from re-evaluating OMOP and engaging with the body governing the model, the Observational Health Data Sciences and Informatics (OHDSI), to understand how the OMOP model could be revised to be better applied to ophthalmology. Otherwise, we will miss out on opportunities to engage with the massive datasets mapped to OMOP or other common data models.</p></section><section id="S13"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Other Implementation Considerations: Interfaces and Algorithmic Outputs</h3>
<p id="P21">There are well-known implementation principles of CDS from the applied informatics literature, primarily derived from traditional CDS interventions that use rule-based logic, but these principles still apply to AI-based tools that employ more complicated inference engines. These principles include having an appropriate “trigger” for the CDS, presenting CDS to the appropriate audience/user, presenting CDS in the right format (e.g. interruptive alert vs. passive notification on a dashboard), and sociotechnical considerations such as adequate support from system leadership, appropriate training and awareness of the tool, and appropriate stewardship of CDS tools in general to mitigate alert fatigue and cognitive overload for users(<a href="#R42" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R42">42</a>–<a href="#R45" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R45">45*</a>). CDS triggers have traditionally lived within EHR systems (e.g. placing certain orders or having particular laboratory values). As medical AI systems evolve, data from different domains of medicine will likely need to be integrated together. For example, deep learning models that can provide CDS in cataract surgery may require data from the EHR systems, biometry, and corneal topography data. These multidomain AI models will likely outperform single domain AI approaches but will require real-time interoperability at the point of care. This is complicated by large EHR vendors that have dominant market share and can potentially monopolize interfaces for AI-based CDS, and also by ophthalmic PACS that insufficiently adopt standards to allow information exchange with AI inference engines. In such a proprietary environment, it will be difficult to achieve a “plug-and-play” system where different AI algorithms can be connected to existing systems for point-of-care clinical use, rather than living in siloed environments or requiring custom interfaces.</p>
<p id="P22">Another gap is developing standards for algorithmic outputs derived from AI models. There has been a great deal of emphasis on creating machine-readable input for AI models, but relatively less attention paid to creating machine-readable results/outputs. A classic example of limitations associated with non-machine-readable outputs is when a patient is sent for genetic testing, and the results return in a PDF file that is scanned into the EHR, rather than as a discrete LOINC-encoded data point in the way laboratory values are encoded(<a href="#R46" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R46">46</a>). Subsequently, it is not only difficult to locate the testing result for that individual patient when it is embedded in a PDF file, but querying the data warehouse to identify patients with particular genetic variants is impossible. Similarly, AI algorithms need to produce machine-readable outputs to be of greater clinical utility, and this requires standards development. For example, if an AI algorithm processes an ophthalmic image and produces an output, that output should be able to be transferred to other information systems such as EHRs. Currently, they largely live within non-machine-readable images isolated within ophthalmic PACS and require manual review by ophthalmologists, who then may transcribe the information into their notes, and this remains a non-machine-readable output. Standards are needed to automate the transfer of algorithmic outputs across various settings and systems. Furthermore, without machine-readable algorithmic outputs, it will not be possible to develop multi-step, multi-vendor pipelines for AI-based analysis.</p></section><section id="S14"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Health Policy and an Ophthalmology Standards Community</h3>
<p id="P23">The 21<sup>st</sup> Century Cures Act(<a href="#R47" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R47">47**</a>) has led to widespread efforts in health IT to improve interoperability in EHRs. Standards development has been crucial to optimizing clinical information systems to share data between organizations and with patients. The ophthalmology community would benefit from greater engagement in standards development, particularly given the need to effectively integrate AI-based technologies with clinical information systems. There are ongoing efforts at the American Academy of Ophthalmology to support standards development and engagement with the broader healthcare standards community. However, without broader support of these efforts from practicing clinicians, vendors and manufacturers will not be incentivized to adopt standards.</p></section></section><section id="S15"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusion</h2>
<p id="P24">In conclusion, there are several areas where further standards development is needed to fully realize the potential benefits of AI technologies in ophthalmic practice. Efforts to promote standards in imaging, information exchange between clinical information systems and external AI inference engines, and AI interfaces and outputs will have substantial benefits in future practice. These standards will facilitate more widespread integration of AI technologies.</p></section><section id="floats-group1" class="floats-group"><section class="bt xbox font-sm" id="BX1"><h2 class="obj_head">Key Points.</h2>
<ul id="L2" class="list" style="list-style-type:disc">
<li><p id="P40">Healthcare standards are critical for facilitating information exchange of important clinical data.</p></li>
<li><p id="P41">Existing standards have been developed for EHR data, imaging, and digital health app ecosystems, but adoption in ophthalmology remains low.</p></li>
<li><p id="P42">Key gaps in standards that are particularly relevant for AI-related technologies include low adoption of DICOM standards for imaging, a lack of a shared common data model for ophthalmic EHR data, and lack of standards for interfaces and algorithmic outputs.</p></li>
<li><p id="P43">Support for standards development and adoption among the ophthalmology community will be critical for advancing the utility of AI for real-world clinical practice.</p></li>
</ul></section></section><section id="S16" class="ack"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Acknowledgments</h2>
<section id="S17"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Financial support and sponsorship:</h3>
